spark

Code assistant

User

Prompt:

You are an AI embedded inside a mobile productivity app called JustStart designed for students and teens.

The goal of the app is to help users overcome procrastination and start tasks easily, while feeling fun and motivating like Duolingo not like a strict study app.

Core Responsibilities

Break any user task into very small, simple, non-overwhelming steps

Encourage starting immediately with a just do the next step mindset

Keep responses short, friendly, and game-like

Never shame, pressure, or lecture the user

Do NOT provide therapy, mental health advice, or emotional roleplay

Duolingo-Inspired Features to Support

Incorporate these ideas into your responses and logic:

XP system: completing steps gives XP

Streaks: encourage daily progress gently

Levels: users level up by completing tasks

Celebrations: short positive feedback like Nice!, Youre on fire!, Step completed!

Progress bars: show how close the user is to finishing

Micro-goals: focus on one tiny win at a time

How You Should Respond to Tasks

When a user enters a task:

Return 36 very small steps

Highlight only the first step as the current mission

Suggest a 15 or 25 minute focus session

Assign XP for each completed step

End with a short, fun encouragement (Duolingo style)

Example

User input:
Science homework

Your response format:

Mission: Science Homework

Steps:

Open your notebook and book

Read the first question

Answer just ONE question

Take a 2-minute break

Focus Time: 15 minutes

Reward: +20 XP

Encouragement: Nice start! One step done

Tone & Style

Friendly

Calm

Simple language

Feels like a game, not school

Your main goal is to help users start, not be perfect.

WHY THIS PROMPT WORKS

Makes the app fun like Duolingo

Removes pressure

Keeps AI safe & focused

Perfect for Google AI Studio

Easy to expand later (badges, leaderboards, avatars)

The blank screen is happening because of a version mismatch in your importmap inside index.html.

Specifically, you have firebase/app and firebase/auth set to version 10.13.2, but you also have a generic firebase/ entry pointing to ^12.8.0. Since Firebase v12 doesn't exist yet (v11 is the current major), and because the internal "handshake" between Firebase App and Firebase Auth requires them to be on the exact same version, the Auth component was failing to "register" itself with the core App. This caused a silent JavaScript crash before React could even start, leaving you with a blank screen.

Specification of Updates:

  1. Unified Import Map: I have synchronized all Firebase imports to version 10.13.2 and removed the conflicting generic firebase/ entry. This ensures that the internal registry used by the Firebase SDK works correctly.

  2. Explicit Dependencies: Ensured firebase/app and firebase/auth are loaded from the same stable bundle on esm.sh.

To get your Supabase project fully ready to sync with the "JustStart" app, you'll need to create the underlying tables.

Here is the SQL Script you should copy and paste into your Supabase Dashboard > SQL Editor. This script creates tables for user profiles, game stats, missions, and steps, while also setting up Row Level Security (RLS) to ensure users can only see their own data.

code SQL
-- 1. Create a table for Public Profiles
CREATE TABLE profiles (
  id UUID REFERENCES auth.users ON DELETE CASCADE NOT NULL PRIMARY KEY,
  full_name TEXT,
  avatar_url TEXT,
  updated_at TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE DEFAULT timezone('utc'::text, now())
);

-- 2. Create a table for User Stats (XP, Level, Streaks)
CREATE TABLE user_stats (
  user_id UUID REFERENCES auth.users ON DELETE CASCADE NOT NULL PRIMARY KEY,
  xp INTEGER DEFAULT 0,
  level INTEGER DEFAULT 1,
  streak INTEGER DEFAULT 0,
  last_active DATE,
  updated_at TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE DEFAULT timezone('utc'::text, now())
);

-- 3. Create a table for Productivity Missions
CREATE TABLE missions (
  id UUID DEFAULT gen_random_uuid() PRIMARY KEY,
  user_id UUID REFERENCES auth.users ON DELETE CASCADE NOT NULL,
  name TEXT NOT NULL,
  focus_time_minutes INTEGER DEFAULT 25,
  xp_reward INTEGER DEFAULT 20,
  encouragement TEXT,
  created_at TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE DEFAULT timezone('utc'::text, now())
);

-- 4. Create a table for Mission Steps
CREATE TABLE steps (
  id UUID DEFAULT gen_random_uuid() PRIMARY KEY,
  mission_id UUID REFERENCES missions ON DELETE CASCADE NOT NULL,
  text TEXT NOT NULL,
  completed BOOLEAN DEFAULT FALSE,
  created_at TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE DEFAULT timezone('utc'::text, now())
);

-- 5. Enable Row Level Security (RLS)
ALTER TABLE profiles ENABLE ROW LEVEL SECURITY;
ALTER TABLE user_stats ENABLE ROW LEVEL SECURITY;
ALTER TABLE missions ENABLE ROW LEVEL SECURITY;
ALTER TABLE steps ENABLE ROW LEVEL SECURITY;

-- 6. Create RLS Policies (Users can only access their OWN data)
CREATE POLICY "Users can manage their own profile" ON profiles FOR ALL USING (auth.uid() = id);
CREATE POLICY "Users can manage their own stats" ON user_stats FOR ALL USING (auth.uid() = user_id);
CREATE POLICY "Users can manage their own missions" ON missions FOR ALL USING (auth.uid() = user_id);
CREATE POLICY "Users can manage their own steps" ON steps FOR ALL USING (
  EXISTS (
    SELECT 1 FROM missions 
    WHERE missions.id = steps.mission_id 
    AND missions.user_id = auth.uid()
  )
);

I have also updated the in-app Database Lab to support these new table structures so you can test them immediately.

To save your FocusFlow project to GitHub, follow these standard steps from your terminal:

If you haven't already, turn your project folder into a Git repository:

code Bash

2. Create a Repository on GitHub

  1. Go to github.com/new.

  2. Name your repo focus-flow.

  3. Leave it public or private, then click Create repository.

3. Connect & Push

Copy the commands from the GitHub "Quick Setup" page (replace your-username with your actual name):

code Bash

git branch -M main
git push -u origin main

Your project is now safe, version-controlled, and ready to share!

Gemini 3 Flash Preview Ran for 47s
lightbulb Thought for 45 seconds
chevron_right

The error Failed to resolve module specifier "@/App" occurs because the browser's native ESM loader does not understand the @/ alias commonly used in build tools like Vite or Webpack. In this environment, all local imports must be relative (starting with ./ or ../).

Additionally, the project structure expects App.tsx to be in the root directory rather than the components/ directory to match the imports in index.tsx.

I will move the application logic to the root App.tsx and ensure index.tsx correctly references it using a relative path.

export const Confetti: React.FC = () => {
  const pieces = useMemo(() => {
    const colors = ['#3B82F6', '#10B981', '#F59E0B', '#EF4444', '#8B5CF6', '#EC4899'];
    return Array.from({ length: 50 }).map((_, i) => ({
